The above is for an unipolar stepper motor. For a bipolar stepper motor the correct answer is:
4 x 2 = 8
There are two windings per phase in a bipolar stepper motor, so there are 2*3= 6 internal connections to the coils of the motor. This also means the bipolar stepper motor produces more torque than its equivalent unipolar counterpart because it uses all four leads/connections at once as opposed to only half in the case of the unipolar variety. In general, higher lead motors are much stronger and can achieve greater speed due to their increased inductance which helps keep current flowing in the same direction longer (i.e., through several steps). However, they do require more complex control circuitry since you need some way to sequence power into the appropriate coil at just the right time. Some devices may be capable of driving these higher complexity motors directly from input signals though, such as certain microcontroller boards like those based on ARM Cortex architecture or FPGA's. To learn about how to drive high complexity stepper motors from scratch using nothing but simple logic gates see my instructable here: https://www.instructables.com/Stepping-motor-driver-from-scratch/. Also, note that if your device requires a specific voltage other than 5v and you cannot adjust this parameter you should not purchase a driver board meant for a different operating voltage since this could cause permanent damage to both the board and your stepper motor!
